summary: “100% consistent with his character,” really?”  First of all, did Rian Johnson even watch the OT?  Second of all, everyone knows...
caption:
“100% consistent with his character,” really?”

First of all, did Rian Johnson even watch the OT? 

Second of all, everyone knows Luke Skywalker started off as a whiny farm boy from Tatooine who grew into becoming a pilot for the Rebellion and learned more about himself through Obi-Wan “Ben” Kenobi and met his friends, Han Solo and Princess Leia and Chewbacca, while saving Leia from the Empire. He blew up the Empire’s superweapon, the Death Star. Then, he trained rigorously with Yoda and continued learn about the Force, only for it to be cut short when he left his training to save his friends. Then, Darth Vader dropped the big truth bomb on him by revealing he, Darth Vader, is Luke’s father. Rather than joining the Dark Side, Luke got out of there by falling down a ventilation shaft of sorts and was probably going to die until he was saved by his friends. After all that, Luke decided that his father, who is the second most evil man in the galaxy, is worth saving. So, he continued to hone his Jedi training and rescued his friend, Han, from Jabba the Hutt then another truth bomb was dropped on him by Obi-Wan who revealed that Leia’s his sister (could’ve mentioned that sooner, Ben). Even after that, he returned to the Rebellion and aided in the Battle of Endor by first helping them groundside until he knew he needed to confront Darth Vader. When he was in Darth Vader’s custody, he kept trying to remind his father that there’s still good in him. Luke was taunted by the Emperor into giving into his anger and Luke said this to the Emperor:

“Never. I’ll never turn to the Dark Side.” *throws his lightsaber away* “You failed, Your Highness. I am a Jedi, like my father before me.”

That quote right there. Luke Skywalker is a Jedi. A perfect Jedi? No. There is no perfect Jedi. Luke learned that anger is an emotion he can control and that it will not lead him down to the Dark Side. Luke learned the truth about his father and believed he could save him, despite everything his father had done to him and his friends. Luke knows that nothing is set in stone. He learned that through his failure to save his friends in Cloud City. And that’s the key word: FAILURE. Luke was an amazing character because we saw him go through trials and tribulations that made him become a better person and a great Jedi at the end. The Luke Skywalker in The Last Jedi wasn’t the Luke we remember because a.) it went against everything Luke learned in the OT and b.) there’s was no build-up to this being who Luke is now.  

Luke Skywalker of the OT versus Luke Skywalker of TLJ are two different characters. One had build-up and one just exists.
